I know I'm incredibly lucky in the fact that I went in with all the hype in the world and was still 100% satisfied throughout the entire experience. I'm so glad I went opening night too, because marketing companies took the soonest chance they could get away with to show things I definitely wouldn't have wanted to know was going to happen when walking into the theater. The weight of my expectations were not only the entirety of my history with loving superheroes and growing up with the MCU since I was like 10 years old, but also all of the extra hype I felt from all the theory videos I saw building up to this. My hopes could have extremely easily crashed and burned, but instead this movie literally felt like it was hand-crafted specifically for me. And I know I'm not alone in that, either. It's everything I've wanted to see on the movie screen since I started loving movies when I was like 3 or 4 years old. It's the first movie I've ever seen to make me feel (for a few weeks at least) like I didn't need to watch movies anymore. I haven't stopped watching this on at least a bi-weekly basis since I first got my copy in August and I don't plan to stop. It now holds an extremely proud spot as my favourite movie of all time and I don't see how any other film could take that spot anymore. But that being said, I also thought that when I walked out of that first Avengers movie, so I'm keeping my hopes wide open. Thank you, Chris. I hope you have a lovely time.

I just don't get people bitching about this movie. First act was slow because it needed to be to set up world and characters, second act was great fan service for long time fans, last act was all the action you could ask from a Blockbuster with satisfying ending to these characters. In an age where Star War, Game of Thrones, Dceu, dark universe etc. Tried to do what Marvel did or create a great finale and failed so horribly without a road map or satisfying ending, you should at least appreciate what they pulled off even if it's not your cup of tea, I am sorry for you but you don't get to call us retards for liking this craft and effort on display.

I think in your review you nailed why I disliked this movie, I go to avengers films to have fun and my argument would be that this film was not much fun to watch. The jokes almost never landed and made me cringe. Also, my main problem is that this movie couldn’t decide whether it was action or a soap opera so it built up all this drama and released in a fairly short time travel sequence all things considered. That part was rushed and sped past like a blur, the movie got where it wanted to go and dashed by it before we really got to enjoy it. The end fight suffered from marvels greatest flaw, we don’t care about thousands of faceless enemies dying, we just see endless hordes that we know don’t matter and showing them being cut down is pointless. Also, they killed Thanos which I loved then retconned him back for the end just like that because they decided “no wait actually we still need this character” I don’t usually what to pick apart Avengers films but this film rushed its good parts and built its film around purely the visuals of the final fight scene. Great review.  Honestly, I went into this movie thinking they could NEVER top what they accomplished with Infinity War.   I thought Infinity War was a true cinematic masterwork, with a "bad guy" we have not seen on screen in such a way since Darth Vader in the original Star Wars trilogy.  Thanos was the best CG character since Gollum in LOTR, perfectly done in a believable way and given such depth that you forget you're watching a digital creation.  How could they ever top that?  Well, to my surprise and delight, they have.  End Game is absolutely the perfect ending to this 10+ year story, and the ultimate payoff for fans.  Honestly, I think in 10 years time they will be studying this in film schools all over the world as the screenwriting and character development in the Marvel Universe movies are impossibly good.  I say impossibly because it should have never worked as well as it did.  These are "super hero" characters that they actually managed to get audiences who never read a comic book invested in.  That's a major feat of storytelling I don't think has ever been done before.

Instead of relying on time travel to bring about a timeline, where "good again triumphs over evil", I would be much more interested in seeing how the MCU continues to develop long after those horrendous events (with half its heroes dead or missing).


Because, in all reality: Thanos seems to be the only one who "gets it". Population growth is exponential, while our universes resources are finite … in this regard, Thanos' actions remind me of what Bill Burr had to say on "population control" (in his standup special  "I'm Sorry You Feel That Way“):

„That's my plan: we should just make babys illegal for, like, the next like twenty–five, thirty years. Right?  Wouldn't that be great? Think about it, somebody is born – three people born every second for one person dying – so if you not make anybody, it's like – bam! – somebody just died. Right? Somebody just fell down some stairs …  somebody just tripped over a skateboard, right?  And you know what? Fucking lanes just openin' up on the highway. Right? You know, you get to work a little sooner, you're in a better mood.  Dude, you get it down to like thirty thousand people. Thirty thousand people would be the shit … Right? Superbowl comes along, everybody can go. Right? […] You wouldn't have to recycle. Dude, if there was thirty thousand people, man, everybody here could literally drive your own tank. You drive a tank, you could throw toxic waste off the top – you could shoot a bald eagle right in the head … nah, there's plenty of them, plenty of them. Dude they're shittin' all over my tank, what the fuck am I supposed to do?“

Of course, the events in Infinity War – in a kind of unfortunate "collateral damage" – cost Spider-Man, Doctor Strange, Star-Lord, Gamora, Groot and others their lives. But, all in all, Thanos is the real hero here :-)

I like the direction they went with all the characters. I hate superhero films. I feel they’re boring and unnecessary but this felt like a film of old, the characters are what sell it and the actors do a tremendous job. Again the action scenes were my least favourite but even they were the best I’ve seen in a superhero film. Everything was just balanced perfectly. I go into movies with critique mode on and break a film down to its core as I’m watching it. Not with endgame. With endgame all that bullshit went out the window and I was there with the characters from beginning to end. I had almost a spiritual awakening with this movie on a total film level. I had never laughed, been so tense or cheered and teared up so much in a movie ever! And I hate and advocate against superhero movies. This is a result of a perfect, tightly crafted script, beautiful performances and a vision beyond visionary that will undoubtably stand the test of time. A+. It was paced terribly and I got bored up until the final fight scene which was full of the awesome goodness that I wanted from this movie.

Overall, it's not a bad movie...but it's not, OMG THIS IS THE BEST MOVIE EVER" material like people are saying. I'd give it a C or a 5/10 personally.

See, I REALLY also don't want to be "that guy" as you put it, but there were just too many things that I didn't like about this movie to give it a positive review.  There were definitely enough things that I DID like, so I'd give it a neutral evaluation.  Trying to keep this a spoiler-free comment in a spoiler-free review, things that just bothered me too much--

-this isn't entirely the fault of this movie but rather that of the previous, but it was similar to The Last Jedi where they take the story to such an unprecedented place that there seems no way to deal with or adapt to the situation, but rather it seems necessary to be undone.

-a BIG problem for me - different characters in this series have different abilities or sets of abilites which are not equal in terms of power and impact that the character can have, and that's fine - Thor and Dr. Strange can do things that have significantly more impact than things that can be done by Hawkeye or Rocket.  But so far, even the more powerful characters (Dr. Strange, Hulk) need to play their role as part of a team and need the help of some of the less powerful characters (Black Widow, Starlord) for the team to succeed in their goals.  To this point, the Avengers franchise has been a really good spokesperson (eh... spokesmovie?) for the concept of teamwork.  But in this movie, there is a character on our team who is so powerful that they don't need the help of other characters - instead, they make the rest of the characters more or less irrelevant.  The producers seem to be aware of this and deal with the problem by finding a reason to remove that character for the majority of the 2nd act, and only reintroduce them at the very end, because the best way for the team to address ALL of their problems would be to sit back and drink beers while this person took care of all their problems single-handedly, and there would be no tension in any part of the movie.

- some things are such a significant part of a character, that they almost define a character - while it may be cool to see another character have that thing, it can bother some people when they do it.

-in the previous movie, a character performs a certain act with a certain McGuffin and things happen immediately with remarkable impact.  In this movie, a different character performs the same action with the same McGuffin, and things take much longer and seemingly with less impact, enough so that a third character needs to do it for the resolution.  Seems inconsistent.

-I respectfully disagree with your assessment that this needed to be a 3 hour movie - most Marvel movies are around the two and a half hour mark, and this could simply be done be removing 15 minutes from the first and last act.  In regards to the first act, we already know how the previous film ended and could anticipate how this would affect our characters.  We didn't need to see FOUR different characters act disconnected, defeated and jaded because of the events and create such a depressing tone - instead, just leave in the one that um... "alters the appearance" of a character, because that was awesome.  Edit out the other three.  As for the final act, it reminds me of LotR-Return of the King where the final resolution takes place, and then the movie goes on and on for what seems like eternity.  Definitely could have saved 15 minutes there too.

-When you make a sequel, there's usually an attempt to revisit but "up the ante" with some events of the first.  As for the tearjerker scenes, the biggest one from the previous movie had me actually crying, and the revisiting of it failed in comparison.

They didn't write themselves into a corner, both Infinity War and Endgame were written as a complete story and shot back to back. They released them a year apart instead of the usual 3. As for the 3 hour run time, if you're with children I can see the beef but honestly audiences are expecting more and a change has already begun to happen in movie length. The 90 min romcom or cartoon is still going to exist but when it comes to huge special effect laden, big budget movies with a large cast of characters we need more than 2 hours to get shit done. This movie was the perfect length and be prepared to see even more start to push for it. It's cheaper to make one 3 hour movie than it is to make two 1.5 hour ones spaced years apart with pre/post production, marketing and the press junket. Just imagine what Infinity War and Endgame would have been like broken up into 3 movies... yeah The Hobbit all over again.

In this movie there's two Thanos' - present Thanos and a past Thanos from a different timeline. Present Thanos won. He did the snap and used the stones to destroy the stones. Then the heroes killed him, thus destroying the most interesting character in the past 11 years

What do they replace him with? A different Thanos that takes place roughly around the time of Guardians of the Galaxy 1. This is a Thanos that doesn't know about Stephen Stange, Antman (though Antman isn't really a power house) or Captain Marvel. Other than what he gleaned from present day Nebula. So what does he do? He takes his entire army and storms earth without any recon

This Thanos makes no sense to me. The only conclusion I have to make is that he doesn't know that the stones are requirements for a stable timeline (after all, present Thanos destroyed them) - if he had just stayed still in the past, the avengers would have had to return the stones to the past and some version of Thanos in the past would have replayed the main timeline

But I guess past timeline Thanos in a universe absent the stones wanted the stones and that was the only way to get them. Confused? I sure was.

But my main beef isn't with plotholes. It's with past Thanos making boneheaded moves. He could have teleported to the present and bided his time. He had spoilers (Nebula), his entire army, his children. If I were him, I would just replay the exact sequence of events - divide and conquer.

If you think IW was an A+, this was a B+)

The movie was mediocre with moments of greatness.

The good:
+ Captain America wielding Mjolnir was rewarding.
+ Everything Ant-Man
+ Scarlet Witch vs. Thanos
+ Most of the final battle
+ Hawkeye scene at the start
+ Nebula
+ Nothing major was changed with the Guardians.

The bad:
- What role does Captain Marvel play in this movie that Thor couldn't have?
- Why make Thor the most BAMF in the MCU in Infinity War only to give him anxiety and make him fat in Endgame?
- The whole support group scene was pointless. The beginnign was so slow.
- Regurgitating the same scenes from Infinity War to get the same emotional reactions was lazy. (see Hawkeye/Black Widow on Vormir and Spidey/Stark at the end.)
- Really, Captain America went back in time to hook up with Peggy? What about her husband and life? No pay-off. What about Sharon Carter? Jesus the Russo's you can't keep up with your own movies?
- Honestly, what the eff. Thor got Stormbreaker and hunted down Thanos in IW only to become a fat fuck, abandon Stark in space and stop seeking revenge? The Thor from IW would have torn the universe apart looking for Thanos.
- Final battle "girl group selfie". You know the scene...
- All the voice overs...
-  The whole Ant-Man selfie scene.
- The whole drunk Thor scene with in the cabin.
- Banner Hulk.
- In the Final Battle I was so hoping when Thanos' ship started shooting into space that it would have been the Silver Surfer/Galactus. You don't just wipe out half of someone's lunch without the doing something about it.
- America's ass, really?
- Every "passing the torch" scene felt forced. The movie was poorly paced.

I now have Russofobia and won't be going to any more Marvel movies unless the have an high audience score. We all know professional reviewers are bought. Thanks for ruining the end to 20+ movies and 10 years.

Before Iron Man came out, you know who read comic books?
"Losers." 


And I was one of them. 
When Iron Man came out, I remember as an avid comic reader thinking "wait? They're actually making a movie out of this? That's impossible! Man, what if they made an Avengers movie one day? That could never happen, too many logistics. But man... wouldn't that be something."


I have never been more honored to be a comic book fan than I am today. 
As I sat there in the exact same theatre where I watched every previous Marvel film, for the last time, I realized how much better cinema was for it. This film was as unbound as the imagination of Stan Lee and Jack Kirby, who never had to let budgetary restrictions or any other nonsense limit their imaginations. All they had to do was draw it. Now movies are only as limited as a writer's imagination, to never be restricted again. 
Thank you Kevin Fiegge. 
Thank you Stan Lee. 
Thank you Jack Kirby.

With that said I had one huge beef with this movie and some minor trivial issues. My biggest disappointment is the way hulk was portrayed not just in this movie but in the entire arch of the character. I loved hulk when he was first introduced in the avengers slowly the character was dumbed down and kind of gelded. He kept getting weaker. In the original infinity war and the animated versions hulk was instrumental. He played a major roll in Thanos demise. I get the whole banner hulk merger. But feel they weakened that character as well. So that’s my big beef. Now, a few things trivial that bothered me enough to mention. I felt like the emotional reunions were to darkened. Should of had more tones of joy and relief. Some of the time travel scenes felt forced and like they were trying to hide the scenes at the same time. There going back to Asgard and trying to show and hide a pivotal character Jane. Also, would have liked to see a bit more power play between captain marvel and thanos not just a head but that made thanos faulted a little. Final thought I love the torch passing from the old captain America to the new one. An epic movie an epic ending definitely will see again.

[spoilers after the  ....... at the very end.]  Saw it last night.  I keep using this phrase as it is what is stuck in my head. Endgame: An exquisite, poetic love letter to 11 years of the Marvel Cinematic Universe.  The fanservice is there but here is the beautiful thing about it.  Unlike the Force Awakens where you really are only referencing 3 prior movies when you do nods to the fans.  (Millennium Falcon lightsaber drone ball)  Marvel has 11 years and 21 movies to dilute the callbacks in.  Nothing felt forced.  Everything felt like it was a memory emerging and when it happened you smiled as anyone who has seen those movies was along for that memory.  It made things feel more impactful.
And respectfully I disagree with Chris on the slow burn on the first 30 minutes.  It's not a slow burn.  Its kindling.  We needed the repercussions to feel real as this is a direct continuation of Infinity War.  We needed to see what happens to not only our heroes but the world.  How it tore them down mentally and physically.  That set the stage for the second half of the movie.  It made their struggle feel all the more real instead of just another battle and struggle to fight over.  We all know they were fighting for all those who vanished.  But that setup made the payoff all the better.

As for the movie itself.  I don't even know what to say.  I'm still unpacking it in my head.  If you come at it like its just another summer blockbuster action film,  you'd be right.   But spend an hour.  Or in my case 3 damn hours laying in bed until 3AM GAH!!  Thinking about it, the Russo brothers weaved a plot that threads its way through most of those 11 years.  Some are obvious due to the plot.  Some are not so obvious until you think about it.  It is a perfect bookend to this series.
.
.
SPOILERS
.
.
.
.
I had a Erika moment last night at 2AM.  I honestly think the MCU is the journey of Tony Stark. Yes you have other super heroes throughout those 11 years. But think about it. Who's character arc has progressed and matured the most over those 11 years? Where the end came full circle to the beginning? News Conference.....I am Iron Man. 
.
.
.

How the film ties up other MCU together into one film is seamlessly brilliant and brings an monumentally outstanding conclusion. I could go on for agesss, there’s so many good things. 

Upmost respect to the cast and crew, to put this film together is a phenomenal achievement. This film and the MCU will now join the elite group of films/series like Harry Potter, LOTR, G.O.T etc. that will likely be remembered and continually watched for hundreds if not thousands of years into the future of humanity, no joke.

Well the verdict is in (no worries, won't give any spoilers away), just my honest impression/opinions on this great movie. It definitely is the epic blockbuster promised. I've only had two disappointments about specific issues, issues that only Marvel purists would/will understand when they watch the movie. But those issues aside, I highly recommend going to watch this movie and also would advise no bathroom breaks or getting munchies. Get all your stuff done before taking your seats and buckle up till the end! I don't know if there's many Marvel purists and not just MCU fans on this channel? And yes there's a big difference between the two, "Marvel purists" are die hard Marvel Universe fans and have been since the 60's-70's and usually have a good collection in their basements and can recall story lines of past till this present day, they know their characters and all that entails from that knowledge. And they (me included) don't like when the MCU strays away too much from the true Marvel characters for their MCU movies. So far, the MCU has done a great job trying to stick to the Marvel characters as close as possible. Which is the biggest reason why they've been so successful for the last 10 yrs with this precious franchise they were gifted with and asked to bring to life on the big screen. 

MCU fans are true fans that have loyally followed the MCU from the start and know more about MCU characters than just casual fans (movie goers) and are ok with any and all changes the MCU made to the original Marvel characters to fit the MCU narratives and specific characteristics traits of the Marvel characters because they don't really know the Marvel Universe comic book characters. Marvel purists on the other hand, know the true Marvel characters like they know their family members and aren't so forgiving and notice quite fast any changes made to any original Marvel characters. Marvel purists are like the gate keepers and are quick to cringe when the MCU makes drastic changes to any Marvel book characters and we're not quiet about it either. The true Marvel universe fan base are what makes the majority of MCU movie goers, they still collect comic books, purchase movie tickets/comic books memorabilia's and also acquire the more expensive collectible items. 

I'm not saying MCU fans don't do the same, but they do it on a much much smaller scale. I don't think a MCU fan would be ready and willing to cough up close to $50 K's for my collection in order for them to acquire a collection (turnkey) instead of starting one from scratch. But a true Marvel purist who most likely already has a collection, would want to take a closer look at my collection and after appraisal would (if able) seriously consider buying my collection to add to their own. Disney/Marvel needs to always consider this and in a small way continue to try to cater to that bottomless well of true Marvel universe purists, which will remain faithful to their last breath, just as long as MCU doesn't stray too far away from the original Marvel characters and understand that any changes, small or big to any character will have a ripple effect in the MCU that they need not only to consider but to work with to balance both characters (one being a Marvel character and the other being a MCU character).  


P.S. My collection is not for sale, I gave it to my son as a family heirloom and he's decided to continue growing it himself even though he knows he could easily get big $ for it right now. His decision actually brought tears to my eyes.

I saw the film this morning at a 03:30 IMAX screening.  After sitting through at least 6 trailers (eternity), it felt like the film would never start.  When it did, the cinema f*cked up by playing the 3D version instead and had to restart with the correct 2D showing... We were initially annoyed but cheered when the showing stopped before getting too far in. 
 
**Giant sigh**

HOWEVER, when the film began to roll it was plain sailing.  People may have an issue with the initial pace that starts slow, however I'd liken it Breaking Bad - ie slow but necessary to really flesh out the world and characters after the events of the snap.  Personally I found the world / character building to be one of the stronger elements of the film, which made the whole thing feel plausible, satisfying and entertaining.  

For those worried about CAPTAIN MARVEL, I fully TRUSTED the Russo brothers ability to *direct* actors and was SATISFIED with how they utilised her...

I've been sceptical on reports about people crying multiple times throughout.  I hate to add to the cliché but I found myself GENUINELY welling up on multiple occasions.  The stakes truly felt real and there was a balanced mix of emotions...

I had a few gripes on certain technical aspects that made me raise an eyebrow... that said, the few bits that didn't work in that respect were, in my opinion, completely overshadowed by all the working elements of the film. 

CONCLUSION, if you do see it theatrically, watch it in IMAX.  Where INFINITY WAR felt a little rushed and borederline lacklustre (thinking of the Battle for Wakanda mainly) - this was the quickest 3 hours I'd ever sat through and I was left wanting MORE by the end...

I disagree. It is a great superhero film, a well developed, impactful, fun, entertaining and satisfying epic event style film, an emotional movie with fantastic acting, writing and directing and a wonderful ending that ties everything up allowing it to go full circle. It is a great culmination and conclusion with plenty of nods, references and Easter eggs to the previous 21 films and the comics. Thanos was great and I immensely enjoyed his and everyone else's character arcs. They even made Hawkeye into a great character. They did everyone justice and set it all up in a fun, funny, entertaining manner. The last hour of the film was freaking phenomenal. I give it a 95/100, 9.5/10 and a solid A. Some cgi could of been better and one or two characters could of been used more but those are nitpicks. It's awesome. Check it out. If you're a superhero fan, a comic book fan or an MCU fan, this movie is for you. If not, you'll still like it. It works as a great character drama film, too. Sorry about ranting. But, I loved it. Also, the 3 hours flew by but it started a little slow. But, it was necessary for character and story growth and was worth it. Don't stay until the ending. There's no mid or post credit scene.

But i personally care and i hate the fact that theyve made the Hulk insanely weak in the MCU! I mean, hes missing most of his abilities, like his invulnerability to magic for exemple, or his ability to adapt to literaly everything or anyone, or his regerenation powers which are the best of all Marvel’s superheros are almost nonexistant in the MCU..even his infinite stamina is missing! Theres a lot more of his powers/abilities that are missing in this version of the Hulk, and the ones that he has are extremely weak! I dont get why theyve made him like that...its ridiculous and very frustrating for a Hulk fan like me. The Hulk has always been my favorite character, ive read everything about him, i know a lot about this character and it sucks that they didnt took advantage of this amazing character! Hes not even close to be like he is in the comics, they should have made him at least a bit closer to how he is in the comics imo. Anyway, like i said its very personal, i love the Hulk so much and i find it very disappointing to have this weak/pahetic version of the Hulk in such an amazing franchise! Because beside the Hulk character, everything else was insanely good in this movie, i really loved it!

‘Twas the night before Endgame, and all ‘round the world
Nervous fans were awaiting how the story unfurled.
They whispered and wondered, How would this all end?
Since one year ago, Thanos killed half their friends.

Be patient, be patient — just one more sleep.
Alarms have been set, they're ready to beep.
The date had now come for the Endgame premiere;
Cannot wait any longer, the conclusion was near.

To the theater they dashed, clutching tickets in hand;
They then took their seats for the 3-hour stand.
The room slowly darkened, the screen had gone black;
Viewers covered in goosebumps from the Endgame soundtrack.

The opening scene: Tony floating in space
With a look of deep sadness betraying his face.
Berating himself, Was all this for naught?
A final sad message for his love Pepper Potts.

Nebula walked on by, a gentle touch on his shoulder;
She sensed something new — Tony’s will had grown bolder.
Not like this, Tony muttered, He’s not getting me too.
And the duo arrived to Avengers HQ.

The audience gasped, they clapped, and they cheered
For the OG Avenger was finally here!
The team now assembled, they needed a plan.
The audience knew: they needed Ant-Man.

Steve worried and worried; he tightened his jaw.
He thought of the plan — Was there any flaw?
Avenge the friends who had fallen: Bucky, Scarlet Witch.
Without hesitation, Let's go get this son of a bitch.

They hopped in their spaceship, Captain Marvel at helm
But poor Scott Lang — stuck in the quantum realm!
On their way to fight Thanos, they followed the stones;
Each hero was ready deep down in their bones.

The mad titan Thanos was waiting with glee,
And where did that bring you? Back to me.
No battle more important; never higher, the stakes.
Together they cried, Whatever it takes.

Their butts, they got kicked! An ass-whooping, if you will;
A Marvel nerd scoffed, They didn’t have Beta Ray Bill..
Back home they crawled, desperation at hand
When Scott Lang arrived in an old, beat-up van!

A time vortex! Scott cried, That’s how we can win!
We have to try, Widow added, no matter how slim.
A new strat was brewing: make the timelines anew.
You trust me? Tony asked. Cap nodded, I do.

They put on new suits, sleek black, white, and red.
Get the stones before Thanos — they’ll time skip instead!
You know your teams and your missions, Cap reassured all;
There’s no time to waste, no more chances to stall.

At this point, dear readers, I can’t guess the plot
But oh, it was glorious! Our heartstrings were taut.
No character safe, truly anything goes
Behind the masterminds of our dear Russo Bros.

But know this, my friends, the story was grand
And we would all witness our heroes’ last stand.
They fell again and again, but never surrendered;
The most beautiful movie a Marvel fan would remember.

With the purple guy bested, the Avengers had won.
Their friends were un-dusted, the fighting was done.
The audience wept, and the credits then rolled.
The saga was finished, the tale had been told.

Like an astral projection came All-Father  Stan Lee
With a tear in his eye for all he could see.
His heroes were heroes; he could want nothing more.
Happy Endgame to all, and to all, Excelsior!

Half of all life across the universe disintegrates when Thanos activates the Infinity Gauntlet,[N 1] including Clint Barton's family. Three weeks later, Carol Danversrescues Nebula and Tony Stark, who are stranded in space following their defeat by Thanos. They return to Earth where they rendezvous with Natasha Romanoff, Bruce Banner, Steve Rogers, Rocket, Thor, Pepper Potts and James Rhodes. The team tries to retrieve the Infinity Stones from Thanos to reverse his actions, but finds that he has destroyed them to prevent any further use. Thanos is decapitated by Thor.

Five years later, Banner has merged with the Hulk and Thor has become the drunken ruler of Asgard's refugees in Tønsberg, Norway. Scott Lang escapes from the quantum realm[N 2] and finds Romanoff and Rogers at the Avengers' compound, theorizing that the quantum realm can allow time travel. The three propose to Stark—now raising a daughter, Morgan, with Pepper—that they travel back in time to retrieve the Infinity Stones and return them to the present to undo Thanos' actions. Stark initially rejects out of concern for Morgan, but relents after reflecting upon the loss of Peter Parker and designs a working time machine.

The reunited Avengers split into groups for their mission. Banner, Rogers, Lang, and Stark travel to the Battle of New York[N 3] to retrieve the Time, Mind, and Space Stones. Banner visits the Sanctum Sanctorum and convinces the Ancient One to give him the Time Stone, and Rogers overcomes undercover Hydraagents and his past self to retrieve the Mind Stone. Lang and Stark's failed distraction enables Loki to escape with the Space Stone. Rogers and Stark travel back further to the U.S. Army's Camp Lehigh in 1970[N 4] to steal both an earlier version of the Space Stone and vials of Hank Pym's size-altering Pym Particles to return home afterwards. The pair succeed, while meeting Peggy Carter and Howard Stark en route.

In Asgard, Rocket and Thor retrieve the Reality Stone from Jane Foster.[N 5] Thor encounters his mother Frigga, whose counsel restores his conviction, and obtains a past version of his hammer, Mjolnir.[N 6] Barton and Romanoff travel to Vormir for the Soul Stone. They learn from its keeper, Red Skull, that it can only be retrieved by sacrificing someone they love. After a struggle between the two, Romanoff sacrifices herself.

On Morag, Nebula and Rhodes steal the Power Stone before Peter Quill can do so.[N 7]Rhodes returns to the present with the Stone, but Nebula is left stranded behind as her cybernetic implants interface with those of her past self, which Thanos exploits and learns of present-day events. He sends the past incarnation of Nebula to the present in present-day Nebula's place.

As Banner activates the Infinity Stones to resurrect everyone killed by Thanos, past Nebula uses the time machine to transport Thanos and his ship from the past to the present day. Rogers, Thor, and Stark confront Thanos, though he overpowers them, even when Rogers proves able to wield Thor's hammer. Thanos summons the Black Order and his armed forces, but the revived Avengers arrive on the battlefield, along with the Sanctum Sorcerers and the armies of Asgard and Wakanda. Present-day Nebula convinces past Gamora to turn on Thanos, and in the ensuing standoff Nebula kills her past self. Stark eventually retrieves and activates the Infinity Stones, which disintegrates Thanos and his army. Stark is mortally wounded in the process.

Following a funeral for Stark, Thor appoints Valkyrie queen of Asgard and joins the Guardians of the Galaxy. After returning the Infinity Stones and Thor's hammer to their original timelines, Rogers chooses to travel back and live his life in the past with Carter. He arrives as an elderly man and passes his shield onto Sam Wilson.

I’m gonna be truthful I didn’t really like endgame. Perhaps I hyped myself up but I felt that it wasn’t completely satisfying and felt rushed and loose in many places, if anything it created more confusion than closure. 

SPOILERS AHEAD!!!!


1. Thor: he was so epic and amazing in IW so I get that they would want to shine light on someone else, but they really just said “fuck it” to Thor’s whole character. He’s character arc lead to something so epic and all we got to see in this final movie was him being fat and basically comedic relief. That felt really cheap to me. 

2. Black Widows death: this one is kinda hard to explain. The only reason why I find this upsetting is because her death ruined the whole idea of an epic final OG6 avenger moment that a lot of people including myself were hyped up about. 

3. The whole time travel plot: I get that I’m no film director or writer, but I felt that it could of been written out better. It seemed like just fanservice trying to incorporate past roles into the scene just because. I know it’s hard to do but the whole team plan, even though it’s the most logical way to go from it kinda split the team apart which bugged me as it leads into the next flaw. 

Lack of og6: the avengers movie should be focused on the avengers team. The last 2 movies basically developed their relationship and hyped it until this. I got that IW wanted to put a lot of secondary characters to weave the whole mcu together but I really hope that in doing that, endgame would be very og6 focussed. It kinda was but they were still split apart which diminishes the epicness of the og6 team. Even so, they didn’t even have that iconic og6 moment which made me super upset. It is their movie series so I really wanted it to really show them together and fighting together as a last tribute to the original team, yet they didn’t even share a fight together so if anything it wasn’t very satisfying and I felt incomplete. 

Cliche moments: I know i might get a bit bashed for this but I found the whole girls fighting together at the end of the movie very forced and cringy, tbh just trying to shove political/feminist stuff to impress the audience which is getting overused and boring, i kind of don’t like that stuff getting overly done and forced into films. All about girl power but not when it’s just shoved in your face. There were other things such as some of the humour which felt forced and dry, wasn’t as memorable as IW even so just idk a lot of scenes in the film I didn’t really click with or enjoyed. 

Hulk/ Bruce Banner: yea that whole character arc was also done shit. Once again I’m not a director or writer so I can’t really say much but as a viewer, I felt that the hulk/ Bruce banner arc was ruined completely in this movie along with Thor. It felt rushed and cheap and didn’t really give a lot of development or closure to Bruce’s character, once again just adding random stuff last minute to try and solve/ end his arc in a crappy way. Not only that but we didn’t see a hulk vs thanos rematch which I and many other were anticipating. 

Steve’s ending: a lot of people have also shared similar views as me in this context which is Steve’s ending. It felt to fanfic/ fan service to just put him back in time to be with Peggy. Yeah it’s cute and he deserves happiness but a lot of plot holes happened because of that; how it could affect the whole timeline and just the fact that he’s choice meant that nothing for his past 10 years in the present day or the risks and responsibilities he had meant to him. Idk I wanted captain to have a heroic epic death but they once again made a cheap send off to which they didn’t pay attention to the massive plot holes that were created. Just seems like poor story writing and how it was executed. 

Yea I know it sounds very nit-picky and im usually those who enjoy movies easily but I feel like as a fan from the very start, I saw all the development and hype of each solo and avenger films that were made and the character arcs that were built to lead up to this 3 hour movie which really didn’t satisfy me as much and just felt very incomplete, inconsistent and rushed/poorly made. I believe they could of established a better storyline that could be a epic rightful tribute and ending to the past amazing films that lead up to this and the og6 avengers which were the start to this whole cool universe. With all the hype and 7 years of story and character creating, i feel like this as a final film was kind of a let down.
There is just 1 issue I have with the entire movie.

Unpopular opinion, but I'm actually disappointed with this film..

NO SPOILERS!
The major problem, to me, is that it has no boundaries. There's tons of stuff happening, things fans really want to see, things I really wanted to see.. But there's just so many ideas crammed into this film, that it becomes a big mess. There's no structure, constant switch of tone from emotion to humor, characters do things that are completely out of character and overboard. Infinity War added a whole lot of things, but knew where to stop. I really don't want to be THAT guy because I love Marvel, but even though this film was very exciting, I don't think it was a success.

Please don't hate. Just my opinion.

I don't think your take on fan service is entirely correct, It's not really about not giving the fans what they want, it's more that it feels sloppy to just pander to your audiences desires (In general terms, I haven't watched any avengers movies). I think the role of a creator is most of the time to give the audience what they didn't know they wanted, for example killing off a character is not something you'd know you want as a viewer but it can often be used as a very powerful tool for giving the audience an emotional reaction.

I'd say a creator should not ask themselves "What does my audience want?" but rather "How can I make my audience feel?". Just my take tho.

I had an amazing experience in the theatre. I went to an 'Avengers Night', and saw Infinity War and Endgame right after each other, with 30 minutes in-between. Everyone was hyped (there were a lot of die hards), and the atmosphere was.... amazing. In both IW and Endgame people started clapping at great moments, people gasped together, cried together, everything together. During the break, 2 or 3 persons started singing a birthday song because it was their friend's birthday. Everyone in the theatre started singing and clapping along (which was around 200 people). After the movie we all got a poster of Endgame (an advertisementposter of the cinema, so part of it isn't Endgame), which is cool. I was with my little brother but people started to ask our opinion anyway, and on the street there was this guy that noticed we saw Endgame and said: 'please no more spoilers I'm gonne watch it tomorrow', and some people gave him false spoilers (like Howard the Duck was great in this). This is just the tip of the iceberg, but this was one of the best experiences in the theatre I ever had. There is one more thing that happened but that is a spoiler, so click away.

Just watched Avengers 4 end game 
Although the "Avengers 4" have no surprise, the script is time travel , and the final boss is still thanos.  But there is barely no disappointment !Shocked to deep ! The rhythm and bright plots are moving without feeling the passage of time!  Laugh and sad point both reached the climax ! Almost all of the most important of the 22 films of Marvel's ten years have been reviewed, and the original characters have been filled up several times better !  The various stalks and bridges have culminated in the Marvel fans who have seen all the ten years movies !  The last big battle is the most Epic and magnificent scene in movie history ! Not only is the scene most Magnificent , but it also brings the audience's mood to the climax !  Beyond what is expected is the sacrifice of the Black Widow and Iron Man ! The damn Marvel ＂killed＂the two most expensive ones.  .  Especially the death of Iron Man, the sensation is the ultimate ! Even me who is almost never sentimental to the movie, it is inevitable that tears came out when I walk out of the theater ! 
Marvel ten years, SUPER EPIC level.  !  Marvel movies has  accompanied us for ten years.  From the Iron Man in 2008, a richman build cool armor, an imaginative science fiction story to the Thor, the Avengers, the Guardians of glaxay and then to the avengers 3 all the characters together, and then to the avengers 4.  The film universe and the story structure are getting bigger and bigger. More and more stories, characters, and settings in the original comic book have been put on the big screen, and the Marvel movie has also developed into a super phenomenon ! Marvel Film has created an era, and accompanied many people through a stage of life. The first time I watched Iron Man movies i was akid , now⋯Avengers 4 is the end of an era.  !  After watching it, my heart can be described as a mixture of five flavors and mixed feelings!  "Avengers 4" is undoubtedly an epic blockbuster ! The success of the Marvel movie universe is also a milestone in the commercial film and the film industry!  It will inspire more creators, and more comics, novels, and series stories will be put on the big screen in the future, and more movie universes will appear.  As the director said, "Avengers 4" is the end and the beginning.  Looking forward to the future DC &Marvel movie, I also look forward to more movie universe.  RIP Stan Lee.  Thanks to the Marvel movie for accompanied us for ten years .  !

I honestly dont understand the culture of looking down on fanservice, especially character based fanservice, in movies like this. Fanservice can be a lot of things. It can make people jump out of their seats and scream along with the audience (spoilers for My Hero Academia movie, you've been warned), a good example of that is seeing Deku and All Might finish off the bad guy in the MHA movie with a Double Detroit Smash. That whole bit was fanservice but it felt amazing. 

Fanservice can also be heartwarming (see the entirety of Kimi no Na Wa or Rascal Does Not Dream of Bunny Girl Senpai)

(Spoilers for My Hero Academia season 3)
And it can even be soul destroying. It's a somewhat subtle example of fanservice that rewards people who really pay attention to the music to give that extra layer of emotion to the situation. In the show the hero All Might is fighting the biggest bad guy in the world. All Might is on his last legs, hes running on fumes and hes very close to dying. All Might is the symbol of peace for the world. Like if Captain America were given Superman levels of strength instead of Black Panther levels. The whole world is watching. And at the last moment, he thinks back to the words of his mentor who died fighting this same villain, and all she says is "do your best, Toshinori (All Mights name)". So he takes a page from his protege's book, something unexpected, he uses his right arm as bait for the villain to block, then hits him with an cross from the other side to knock him off balance. And then, finishes him off with one final, superman level punch. Perfect form and everything. And the music finally swells, and as he slams the villain into the ground so hard that he creates a tornado that lifts sections of buildings off the ground around them. The music goes from a dark menace, to a building anticipation, and then the final fanfare. And it's not just any swell, it's All Mights theme. The "superman has come to save us" melody. Honestly I'm crying just writing about it. And it becomes even more painful and sad but also triumphant when it's made clear that, even though he won, All Might used the last of his power and will never be able to be the world's symbol of peace again.


So yeah, fanservice isnt just cheap jokes that should be looked down on. There is nothing wrong with rewarding your fans for their attachment to your work by giving them emotional payoff.

If you are mindless and doesn't have any judgment capacity, you will think this movie is awesome; however, if you can think, this is the worst marvel movie, besides the VFX.

There are so many things wrong with this movie, that is hard to describe everything. If you make an analysis based only in the story and the direction, it`s already really bad. The movie, tells something and does another, the time travel is heavily bad; Hulk says that is impossible to change the present, however, they simply destroy everything, Thor gets his hammer from the past; Nebula kills herself; Black Widow sacrifice herself to get the Soul Stone, but Gamora still dead in the present.

Superherowise, this movie is also horrible, through the movie, you don`t feel you are seeing heroes talking to each other, but actors interacting with one another dressing like superheroes. The movie is a comedy movie with superheroes, action exists only in the final part of the movie.

Politicalwise, this movie is even worse, the feminism been pushed down our throats, Captain America passing over his shield to Falcon instead of Bucky, his best friend and with similar characteristics of his. Captain Marvel, the worst character in movies so far, arrogant and insanely overpowered; The future Avengers are all girls, Hawkeye Daughter; Ironman Daughter; Antman daughter; and even Peper Potts appears of nowhere if a nanotech armor, Really? But the thing that is worse than all, is Cap, the character who represents the great and old America, turning into a selfish and egoist guy, traveling back in time to be with Megan Carter, forgetting about Sharon, and acknowledging that Tony was right, the guy who made all the bad decision, trading freedom to false security, like the government tries to do.

In a Nutshell, this is a movie trying to brainwash you to think the what is bad is good and what is good is bad, with horrible writing, but great visual effects.

***No Spoiler Comment*** Endgame is indeed an awesome movie, but not a flawess one. The thing that may down and hurt Endgame a little is just the plot devices/convienences. There are some. When you watch them, you just realized that such person was somewhere at some perfect time just to... Or somebody is changed just because.... And so on and on. 

But!

Endgame is a different type of movie. There's so much to cap and some many thing to bring to an end, that makes you overlook the plot devices, you understand why they make use of those conveniences to get the story going and to hit the finale of this 11 years of film making they have to delivery. 

Movie wise, Infinity War is a better movie. Even the Avengers 2012 is. However in the big picture, when you see what Endgame means and represents you gotta say it's the biggest and more robust and more important movie of all MCU. Also the one that hits you the hardest and probably the one that will stick the most in your memory.

Trash, absolute trash. I can’t believe so many ppl have talked about how great this thing was. There’s so many little moments of the film that I hated, but the concept of the film was the thing I hated most. They didn’t change their approach or strengthen themselves at all. They just went back in time to undo everything. It’s so fucking stupid to me that the Thanos they fight in the climax, isn’t even the Thanos that beat them in the first place! Like what, i thought the whole purpose of the movie was to strengthen themselves to confront Thanos again, and only after they make it past Thanos can they undo what he did. Not jus fucking ambush the guy and lop his head off. 

On top of that, it’s fucking stupid to resurrect 3.5 billion people 5 years after they’ve died. Not only is that shit jus completely unnatural (Avengers need to read the Monkey’s Paw), but that would just throw the world into chaos all over again. Could y’all imagine if 3.5 billion people jus showed up on the planet? What the hell do you do from there? Everybody that lost a spouse and has moved on to a new relationship is in trouble. Everybody who’s lost someone and has managed to move on is just being punished.
You can’t just disappear and reappear back in ppl’s lives and expect it to all be the same. I had a feeling that this movie was gone disappoint me, but damn I didn’t think it’d be that bad. Thanos went out like a punk man. And don’t even get me started on Captain America wielding that damn hammer like he was the next God of Thunder 😒 I get him lifting up Mjolnor, but did he really shoot lightning out that bitch? Man get outta here

This movie was nuts, first of all I really liked how a lot of the beginning was focused on the characters dealing with all that’s happened and really focusing on emotion rather than just action, it is slow but it’s in no way boring, also the characters were still really great, Hulk is taken in a direction that admittedly at first I thought was really weird but I got used to it after a while, Thanos doesn’t get as much attention as he did in Infinity War but he’s still a great character and it’s great whenever he’s onscreen, and this has gotta be the best I’ve ever seen from Hawkeye, I’ve always thought he was a decent character but nothing great, but here I thought he was awesome and the interactions between everyone were great, the movie does have a lot going on especially since as everyone suspected time travel is involved, so as usual with time travel it’s a little hard to wrap your brain around everything, there’s no way you can fully understand it in just 1 viewing, they do do some really interesting stuff with the time travel element though, the action is amazing, there’s this big battle in the middle of the movie and holy shit is it cool, same for the climatic battle, 2 of the best superhero movie throwdowns I’ve ever seen, they’re so much fun, and Jesus Christ, there’s a moment with Cap during 1 of those battle scenes that I’m not gonna spoil but holy shit I literally wanted to scream it was so awesome, with the direction they took Thor I can see a lot of people not liking it but I thought it was interesting, some of it admittedly didn’t work but for the most part I was fine with it, the movie does have a bit of Back To The Future 2 syndrome, where sometimes the time travel can get a little *too* convoluted for its own good, they do a lot and most of it works but some thing are a little questionable, there is a lot of enjoyment to be had with the time travel element particularly for long time fans of the MCU though, and yeah quite of few of our predictions on who’s getting un-snapped came true, but since we all saw it coming I wasn’t really that bothered by it, and oh my god, the final act of this movie is amazing, along with that amazing battle you also have the ending and let me tell you I nearly cried, the way they choose to end this movie just left me stunned, my heart was melting and I loved it, with where all the characters ended up it’s really interesting thinking about where the MCU is gonna go from here, overall I had a blast with Endgame, it was emotionally satisfying, exciting, funny and a great way to finish off this story arc in the MCU. 9/10

I just think it would have been so much more poetic.

This movie is pretty much contrived writing for the sake of contrived writing. The Butterfly Effect, a defining rule in any story involving time machines, is put on a shelf to justify all of the events happening in the movie. The explanation for how the future doesn't change even in case of severe altering of the past is flimsy at best, and completely terrible at worst. The excuse is pretty much that the current lineup of the Avengers create new timelines every time when they alter the past, while their own future gets untouched. Okay, let's believe that's how time travel works. That way, The Avengers have created multiple timeliness in which their other selfs will be faced with different outcomes of the events we already know. For example, in the original timeline of the first Avengers movie, the events are altered so that Loki escapes before he is sent to Asgard and he manages to get the Tesseract back. So in that timeline, Loki won. And in that same timeline, Hydra will figure out that Cap knows that they infiltrated the government because the future Cap pretends at one point to be Hydra, but the past Cap doesn't know of that. So Hydra will either try to kill Cap before he can even understand what is what or they will the start the Project Insight before the events of the Winter Soldier. Then they alter the timeline of Thor 2, where Rocket steals The Ether from Jane Foster before Malekith attacks Asgard, and that version of Thor will also lose his hammer because the future Thor stole it. And you maybe asking what's the problem here? The problem is that all of those different timelines are altered for the worse and they put those versions of the Avengers in the same jeopardy the new ones are facing. The future Avengers destroyed timeline of the past Avengers to save their own. And not only that, there's a big possibility of the past Avengers figuring out what has happened, and they can easily try to do what the future Avengers did and they can also try to go back in time to alter their timeline at the expense of others. Seriously, this movie is mind-fuckingly convoluted. Someone needs to write a tie-in book for the movie where all of this nonsense is at least explained at some capacity. Like in Interstellar, which got a tie-in book written by the scientist who supervised the science on the movie.

Message to Marvel Fans 
Just saw the Avengers Endgame Movie....Twice
Review Brief!!! NO Spoilers!!!
The movie is three hours long so buy a snack or hide it from the security at your movie theater. Without spoilers, I can tell you that this movie has a lot of flaws. I've started negative to tell y'all that I don't really like it. I've seen all the movies and read mostly every comic book related to these events with Thanos. That includes even an idea or a mention of Thanos. There are to many directions in the movie only to create lots of plot holes. The introduction of Endgame is strong, but it didn't deliver, until the climax action scenes. I feel like I was watching Episodes of Avengers, instead of a movie. I laugh at many characters dialogue and had some emotions parts within the middle of the film. Then I've re-watched the movie... 😞The new characters didn't had any character development. You can certainly tell which characters this movie is made for, due to their salary and contract agreements, they didn't want to expand more. I fully understand that situation however, they used the same DAMN MINERAL. OVER AND OVER AGAIN! The movie is fill with great moments, but it's definitely a Disney movie. 😓 The creatively isn't there for this big budget firm.

I personally loved it, i think its the best of the franchise...i wont go into spoilers or anything, but this movie made me go through all kind of emotions, i even cried at the end ffs!! It has everything, its really a great movie, thats how epic superhero movies should be made! Its a 10/10 for me. 
Now on a very personal note, theres one thing that i really didnt liked, its something that has been bugging me since the very beginning..i know most people wont even care. But i personally care and i hate the fact that theyve made the Hulk insanely weak in the MCU! I mean, hes missing most of his abilities, like his invulnerability to magic for exemple, or his ability to adapt to literaly everything or anyone, or his regerenation powers which are the best of all Marvel’s superheros are almost nonexistant in the MCU..even his infinite stamina is missing! Theres a lot more of his powers/abilities that are missing in this version of the Hulk, and the ones that he has are extremely weak! I dont get why theyve made him like that...its ridiculous and very frustrating for a Hulk fan like me. The Hulk has always been my favorite character, ive read everything about him, i know a lot about this character and it sucks that they didnt took advantage of this amazing character! Hes not even close to be like he is in the comics, they should have made him at least a bit closer to how he is in the comics imo. But no, they had to make him extremely weak..hes missing most of his powers, and the ones he has are very weak! I mean even his strength is not even close to be how it should be, as well as his regeneration powers, hes barely able to heal himself when hes hurt, when in fact the Hulk has the best regeneration powers of all Marvel’s superheros! 
Anyway, like i said its very personal, i love the Hulk so much and i find it very disappointing to have this weak/pahetic version of the Hulk in such an amazing franchise! Because beside the Hulk character, everything else was insanely good in this movie, i really loved it!

‘Twas the night before Endgame, and all ‘round the world
Nervous fans were awaiting how the story unfurled.
They whispered and wondered, How would this all end?
Since one year ago, Thanos killed half their friends.

Be patient, be patient — just one more sleep.
Alarms have been set, they're ready to beep.
The date had now come for the Endgame premiere;
Cannot wait any longer, the conclusion was near.

To the theater they dashed, clutching tickets in hand;
They then took their seats for the 3-hour stand.
The room slowly darkened, the screen had gone black;
Viewers covered in goosebumps from the Endgame soundtrack.

The opening scene: Tony floating in space
With a look of deep sadness betraying his face.
Berating himself, Was all this for naught?
A final sad message for his love Pepper Potts.

Nebula walked on by, a gentle touch on his shoulder;
She sensed something new — Tony’s will had grown bolder.
Not like this, Tony muttered, He’s not getting me too.
And the duo arrived to Avengers HQ.

The audience gasped, they clapped, and they cheered
For the OG Avenger was finally here!
The team now assembled, they needed a plan.
The audience knew: they needed Ant-Man.

Steve worried and worried; he tightened his jaw.
He thought of the plan — Was there any flaw?
Avenge the friends who had fallen: Bucky, Scarlet Witch.
Without hesitation, Let's go get this son of a bitch.

They hopped in their spaceship, Captain Marvel at helm
But poor Scott Lang — stuck in the quantum realm!
On their way to fight Thanos, they followed the stones;
Each hero was ready deep down in their bones.

The mad titan Thanos was waiting with glee,
And where did that bring you? Back to me.
No battle more important; never higher, the stakes.
Together they cried, Whatever it takes.

Their butts, they got kicked! An ass-whooping, if you will;
A Marvel nerd scoffed, They didn’t have Beta Ray Bill..
Back home they crawled, desperation at hand
When Scott Lang arrived in an old, beat-up van!

A time vortex! Scott cried, That’s how we can win!
We have to try, Widow added, no matter how slim.
A new strat was brewing: make the timelines anew.
You trust me? Tony asked. Cap nodded, I do.

They put on new suits, sleek black, white, and red.
Get the stones before Thanos — they’ll time skip instead!
You know your teams and your missions, Cap reassured all;
There’s no time to waste, no more chances to stall.

At this point, dear readers, I can’t guess the plot
But oh, it was glorious! Our heartstrings were taut.
No character safe, truly anything goes
Behind the masterminds of our dear Russo Bros.

But know this, my friends, the story was grand
And we would all witness our heroes’ last stand.
They fell again and again, but never surrendered;
The most beautiful movie a Marvel fan would remember.

With the purple guy bested, the Avengers had won.
Their friends were un-dusted, the fighting was done.
The audience wept, and the credits then rolled.
The saga was finished, the tale had been told.

Like an astral projection came All-Father Stan Lee
With a tear in his eye for all he could see.
His heroes were heroes; he could want nothing more.
Happy Endgame to all, and to all, Excelsior!

text:
Im so sorry about this bro..

After Thanos uses the Infinity Stones, Clint Barton's family are turned to dust, along with half of all living creatures in the universe. Nebula and Tony Stark are stranded in space following their defeat by Thanos, but are returned to Earth by Carol Danvers and reunited with the surviving Avengers. The team formulate a plan to steal the Infinity Stones back from Thanos and use them to reverse his actions, but learn upon finding him that he had used the stones a second time to destroy them, preventing their further use. In anger, Thor kills Thanos.

Five years later, Scott Lang escapes from the quantum realm to discover that five years had passed, and that Hope van Dyne, along with half of the population, had disappeared. Lang goes to Black Widow and Captain America, and explain that while five years had passed, only five hours had passed for him in the quantum realm. The three go to Stark, who is now raising a child with Pepper Potts, and explain their theory that the quantum realm can be used to go back in time and steal the Infinity Stones before Thanos is able to collect them. Stark initially rejects their proposal with concern about risking parenthood, but after reflecting upon the loss of Peter Parker decides to test computer models for quantum time travel. He succeeds in finding a model that works, and is further encouraged by Potts to act after having further doubts.

The Avengers are reunited with a plan – Banner, Captain America, Lang, and Stark embark to retrieve the Time, Mind, and Space stones from New York during the Avengers' battle with Loki in 2012. Banner goes to the Sanctum Sanctorum, where he is informed by the Ancient One that taking the Time Stone from her timeline would prevent Doctor Strange's future efforts to stop Kaecilius from destroying the laws of nature. She concedes the Time Stone to Banner however, after he informs her that Strange had given Thanos the stone in his timeline, implying Strange had intended for a specific sequence of events to occur for Thanos to be defeated, including Banner taking possession of the Time Stone. Banner also promises the stones' return to her timeline in order to prevent any ill effects. Lang and Stark attempt to steal the Space Stone – Lang gives Stark's past self a cardiac arrest by pulling a circuit in his artificial heart and causing a scene, while Stark steals the briefcase when nobody is looking. Their plan is thwarted as Stark drops the briefcase after he is accidentally hit by the Hulk. Loki then uses the Space Stone to escape custody. Captain America succeeds in stealing the Mind Stone from undercover Hydra agents, but stumbles across and fights his past self, whom mistakes him for a disguised Loki. Lang returns to the present while Captain America and Stark devise a plan to steal the Space Stone from a U.S. Army installation in the 1950s, while stealing further vials of fluid in order to make the journey back home. While there, Captain America sights Peggy Carter and Stark converses with his father Howard before returning.

Rocket and Thor travel to Asgard to retrieve the Reality Stone before Malekith uses it against the nine realms. While in Asgrad, Thor is reminded that his mother, Frigga, would die soon and has a chance encounter with her while Rocket steals the Reality Stone from Jane Foster. The two return to Earth after Frigga counsels Thor and he retrieves his hammer. Nebula and War Machine travel to Xandar to steal the Power Stone before Peter Quill does. As War Machine returns to the present with the Power Stone, Nebula malfunctions and remains on Xandar. Her memories are accidentally transferred to her past self, which Thanos uses to learn that he would ultimately succeed in his plans to wipe out half the universe and that the Avengers are going back in time to retrieve the Stones before he does. Barton and Black Widow travel to Vormir to retrieve the Soul Stone, though are conflicted when Red Skull, keeper of the Soul Stone, informs them that the stone can only be retrieved by sacrificing someone they love. The two fight over who would make the sacrifice, and Black Widow ultimately takes the fall, with Barton taking the Soul Stone back to Earth and informing the other Avengers of Black Widow's death.

After Nebula is captured by Thanos and her time travel abilities given to her more loyal past self, the past Nebula uses Banner's time machine to transport Thanos and his army to the Avengers' base. The Avengers task Banner to use the Infinity Stones to bring everybody killed by Thanos back. He succeeds, though they are attacked by Thanos, who reduce the base to rubble. The past Nebula is killed by her future self as she attempts to take the Infinity Stones from Hawkeye, while Captain America, Thor, and Stark confront Thanos, who decides to instead use the Infinity Stones to destroy the universe and create one in his vision. Soon after Thanos' army lands on Earth, T'Challa appears before Captain America, along with all of the Avengers revived by Banner, before launching an assault on Thanos and his army. After a lengthy battle during which Stark is reunited with Parker and Gamora is reunited with Quill, Thanos wrestles with numerous Avengers for the Infinity Stones. Risking certain death, Stark rips the Infinity Stones from Thanos' hand and uses them to turn Thanos and his entire army into dust. Parker and Potts console Stark as he dies from the radiation emitted from the Stones.

Following the battle, the Avengers hold a funeral for Stark, whose artificial heart is floated into the sea. Thor makes Valkyrie the Queen of Asgard and joins the Guardians of the Galaxy. Meanwhile, Captain America is tasked to go into the past to return the stones and Thor's hammer to their original timelines, but decides not to return to the present and to instead live the rest of his life in the past with Carter. As an older man, he appears before Falcon and gives his shield to him.

Stark records a message to Pepper essentially saying goodbye as is heard in the trailer/teasers.
Captain Marvel brings the ship back to Earth saving Iron Man and others.
Thanos is found in his garden after having also destroyed the stones.
Thor decapitates Thanos.
Movie picks up 5+ years later.
Remaining Avengers are scattered and living in dark times.
Ant Man tells others of Quantum Realm, they realize they may be able to make a time machine of it.
Tony and Pepper are married. She's pregnant with their daughter, Morgan.
Professor Hulk helps build the time machine.
Black Widow retrieves Hawkeye who had gone dark.
Fat Thor is hanging out with Korg and Meik.
Most go back to the Battle of New York to start getting stones from the past.
Professor Hulk retrieves the Time Stone. (The Ancient One may or may not be the person to give it to him.)
Cap has to say Hail Hydra to Crossbones to get the briefcase that contains the Tessaract.
Trying to work around past events to get stones, Loki gets away with the Tessaract.
Past Cap and Present Cap run into each other, Old Cap thinks Present Cap is Loki in disguise which is why they fight.
Thor and Rocket go to Asgard to retrieve the Aether from Jane Foster's body. This is when Thor retrieves Mjolnir.
War Machine and Nebula go to Morag.
Black Widow and Hawkeye go to Voromir.
There can only be one Soul Stone. There's no past and present version, only the stone. This is what alerts Thanos to what they're doing because the soul stone vanishes from the gauntlet.
Cap and Iron Man have to go even further back in time to get the Tessaract since Loki stole the last one.
Stan Lee cameo happens.
While in old SHIELD location, additional quantum particles needed are stolen so they can keep time traveling.
War Machine and Nebula get stone before past Starlord does.
Past Nebula fights Present Nebula and takes her place back to the present.
Hawkeye and Black Widow fight over who will be the sacrifice needed to get the Soul Stone.
Black Widow ends up being the one to die sumoning the Soul Stone.
Characters back to present, gauntlet is recreated.
Professor Hulk wields the gauntlet and undoes things but is hurt as a result.
Dusted are heard in the Soul Stone, leads to it being undone.
Nebula uses the Quantum teleporter to bring Thanos, Avengers HQ is destroyed.
After undusting, Present Nebula kills Past Nebula.
Thor wields Mjolnir and Stormbreaker to battle Thanos.
Cap is able to pick up and wield Mjolnir during this battle.
The Black Order is summoned as well.
Portaling in, the rest of the dusted appear to help the battle.
Pepper shows up to help suited up as 'Rescue.'
Ant Man becomes Giant Man.
The gauntlet is passed around during battle, Spiderman ends up with it.
Captain Marvel shows up and destroys Thanos' ship and gets the gauntlet from Spiderman.
Thanos eventually gets to the gauntlet and tries to snap but it fails.
Iron Man suicides via snap (a middle finger technically) to dust Thanos and the Black Order.
"I am Iron Man" is said in that moment.
Funeral for Iron Man is held, Tony's recorded message is played.
Iron Man stays dead.
New Asgard is created on Earth.
Hawkeye starts teaching his daughter to take over as Hawkeye one day.
Cap travels back in time again.
Old Man Steve returns and passes on the Captain America title.
Captain Marvel is tasked with taking the stones and separating them essentially creating the Infinity Watch.
Flashback of Cap dancing with Peggy. They're married. He was her husband all along.
No after credit scenes, a montage of all the people who made the movies leading up to Endgame.
Edit: Some adjustments now that the final version of the movie is out.
Morgan is born and a couple of years old already.
Thanos actually figures out the plan to undo things when Past Nebula and Present Nebula cross wires a bit and Present Nebula’s memory of the plan is seen by Thanos.
Valkyrie is made Queen of New Asgard
Cap travels back in time to return the stones, Captain Marvel was not tasked to do so.
Bucky isn’t the one who gets the Captain America title, it’s Falcon which is more in line with the Old Man Steve story.

Just saw it and it definitely gave a sense of closure. There were tears in my eyes multiple times and I think a lot of the characters got the ending they deserved. I would give it an 8.5 out of 10. I do however have a few major gripes with it SPOILERS:

-I feel like they ruined Thor’s character... I get that he’s always had a sense of humor since ragnorok, but really? He’s such a slob now it’s ridiculous. I so badly wanted to see prime Stormbreaker Thor fight Thanos, but all we got was the out of shape drunken one.
-Social justice is everywhere, including a bit in Endgame. The movie had a great example of how to do a female empowering scene and how not to do one. The cringey captain marvel scene taking the gauntlet with all her lady helpers was trying way too hard, but they made up for it with the passing of Asguardians ruler to Valkyrie. I was so proud. 
-Captain Marvel was more likeable in this movie, but she’s still ridiculously overpowered, and was basically just a cop out in the final battle. Her superpower is to just fly through everything lol. 
-How THE FUCK did tony use the gauntlet (even if just for a few seconds) if Hulk just barely survived using it? Canonically it doesn’t make any sense, although the scene itself was absolutely incredible.
-Speaking of Hulk, if feel like if IW was emasculating for him, Endgame was even worse. His character is now a nerd in a handicapped brutes body. The professor Hulk thing didn’t work for me, they should have saved that for its own movie or something. 
Other than that, it was amazing. You get a lot of throwback and references at the end that give you a sense of how far you’ve come with these characters, and it brought tears to my eyes. Thank you, Marvel, for the wonderful journey.

Guys, guys, guys....I've just finished watching Avengers Endgame about 20 mins ago. and Nothing! Absolutely NOTHING will prepare you for a 3 hour Geekfest! We in the Philippines saw the movie 6hours ago and the whole theater I was on was cheering and crying whilst (again) personalities dear to the fans gave their swan song. And lemme tell you, the Net rumors about Steve Rogers saying farewell, well, It's a farewell but on a methaphorical, time- tampered goodbye kind of way, lemme just tell all the fans, Nothing that the Net rumors / plot theories describe what's gonna happen within the last Hour. Absolute Geekfest! The whole theater, young and old, able and disabled, war-torn geek and MCU newbie, everyone jumped, cheered and cried(I mean, massive wailing!) at A certain Hero's funeral service. He was there at the beginning, He was there at the end. and if you think the Captain Marvel movie was women empowerment, fellow geeks, you have no idea what Avengers Endgame is gonna show. The women! The Women! The whole marvel universe women!!! are gonna steal some glory for only a few moments BUT the moment was GLORIOUS!!! Even thor's coming in wakanda in Infinity War never comes close to it! and YES!!!! Captain America Wields a weapon he previously thought himself unworthy to bear(wink, wink!). And the immortal lines "Avengers! Assemble!!" When the good Captain utters it, not a few were having tears of joy. Well, I've spoiled enough folks, I'm gonna watch it again a few hours from now. Lastly, Thanos shows why he is the meanest, most egotistical, and unbelievably convincing Badass in the universe. I ca'nt type here what Cap Marvel does to him, though.... Excelsior! ...oh, Stan Lee has a cameo, it's fast, just watch for it!

**WARNING, MY REVIEW / PARTIAL SPOILERS AHEAD**



I saw the film this morning at a 03:30 IMAX screening.  After sitting through at least 6 trailers (eternity), it felt like the film would never start.  When it did, the cinema f*cked up by playing the 3D version instead and had to restart with the correct 2D showing... We were initially annoyed but cheered when the showing stopped before getting too far in. 
 
**Giant sigh**

HOWEVER, when the film began to roll it was plain sailing.  People may have an issue with the initial pace that starts slow, however I'd liken it Breaking Bad - ie slow but necessary to really flesh out the world and characters after the events of the snap.  Personally I found the world / character building to be one of the stronger elements of the film, which made the whole thing feel plausible, satisfying and entertaining.  

For those worried about CAPTAIN MARVEL, I fully TRUSTED the Russo brothers ability to *direct* actors and was SATISFIED with how they utilised her...

I've been sceptical on reports about people crying multiple times throughout.  I hate to add to the cliché but I found myself GENUINELY welling up on multiple occasions.  The stakes truly felt real and there was a balanced mix of emotions...

I had a few gripes on certain technical aspects that made me raise an eyebrow... that said, the few bits that didn't work in that respect were, in my opinion, completely overshadowed by all the working elements of the film. 

CONCLUSION, if you do see it theatrically, watch it in IMAX.  Where INFINITY WAR felt a little rushed and borederline lacklustre (thinking of the Battle for Wakanda mainly) - this was the quickest 3 hours I'd ever sat through and I was left wanting MORE by the end...

My screening got somewhat worse, because of hardcore Marvel fans overreacting in the theater.  The laughs, the clapping, the wailing... It took me out of the movie couple times. There were some moments of pure fan service - but, the irony: the fans in my screening robbed me of the satisfaction I should get from fan service. 
Almost every movie has plotholes - but when you enjoy the movie, even when plotholes are important, you don't think about them as much. This movie established some rules, just to break them. Structure of this movie raises issues with overall MCU continuity. Inconsistency of power/endurance of characters detracted from enjoyment of this movie as well.
Remember when people were upset about how the Luke Skywalker character didn't match their expectations in Last Jedi? Yup, this kind of can of worms is open all over again in Endgame.
I liked some character arcs, I liked how some of them were wrapped up - but I don't want to say anything more because it'd be huge spoilers. However, there was one particular interaction after main story got resolved that weirdly mirrored a scene from infinity war, and I felt like they missed an opportunity there.
This movie relies on the context of the rest of MCU to be appreciated to the full extent, with emphasis on Infinity War; and it relies on some spoilers.
All things considered, in my opinion Endgame is weaker than Infinity War - but I would pin it above Civil War. I recommend watching this movie - but also, I'd suggest not to inflate your expectations.
